# Git Stash â€” Explanation & Commands

`git stash` is used to **temporarily save uncommitted changes** so you can switch branches or work on something else without committing unfinished work.

It acts like a **temporary storage (shelf)** for your changes.

---

## ðŸ§  Why Use `git stash`?

Use stash when you have changes but need to:

* Switch branches
* Pull latest code
* Fix an urgent bug
* Pause current work without committing

Instead of committing incomplete code, you can stash it and restore it later.

---

## ðŸ“¦ What Happens When You Stash?

```
Working directory â†’ saved in stash â†’ working directory becomes clean
```

Your files revert to the last committed state.

---

## ðŸ›  Common `git stash` Commands

### âœ… Save current changes

```bash
git stash
```

---

### âœ… Save stash with a message

```bash
git stash push -m "Work in progress on login feature"
```

---

### âœ… View stashed items

```bash
git stash list
```

Example:

```
stash@{0}: WIP on feature/login
stash@{1}: WIP on payment
```

---

### âœ… Apply last stash (keep it saved)

```bash
git stash apply
```

---

### âœ… Apply and remove stash

```bash
git stash pop
```

---

### âœ… Apply specific stash

```bash
git stash apply stash@{1}
```

---

### âœ… Delete a specific stash

```bash
git stash drop stash@{0}
```

---

### âœ… Remove all stashes

```bash
git stash clear
```

---

## ðŸ§­ Example Workflow

```bash
git stash
git checkout main
git pull
git checkout feature/login
git stash pop
```

---

## ðŸ§  Simple Summary

`git stash` allows you to:

* Save unfinished work temporarily
* Clean your working directory
* Restore work later when ready

